Backup and Restore Images and Containers with Podman
Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Use podman save and podman load to backup and restore container images
Use podman commit to create new images from running containers
Understand practical use cases and limitations of these operations
Prerequisites
A Linux system with Podman installed (RHEL 8+ or Fedora recommended)
Basic familiarity with container concepts and Podman commands
Internet access to pull container images
1GB+ free disk space for image operations
Lab Setup
Verify Podman is installed:

podman --version
Expected output: podman version 3.x.x or higher

Pull a sample image for testing:

podman pull docker.io/library/alpine:latest
Task 1: Save an Image to Tarball
Objective
Learn to export container images to portable tarball files for backup or transfer.

Steps
List available images:

podman images
Note the IMAGE ID or REPOSITORY:TAG of your alpine image.

Save image to tarball:

podman save -o alpine_backup.tar docker.io/library/alpine:latest
-o: Specifies output file
Last argument is the image reference
Verify the tarball:

ls -lh alpine_backup.tar
file alpine_backup.tar
Expected: A .tar file of ~3MB

Troubleshooting
If you get "no such image", verify the exact image name with podman images
Ensure you have write permissions in the current directory
Task 2: Load an Image from Tarball
Objective
Learn to restore container images from previously saved tarballs.

Steps
First, remove the original image:

podman rmi docker.io/library/alpine:latest
Load image from tarball:

podman load -i alpine_backup.tar
Expected output showing the image being loaded

Verify restored image:

podman images
Should show the alpine image again

Key Concept
Loading preserves the original image name and tags
The loaded image will have the same layers as the original
Task 3: Commit Container to New Image
Objective
Learn to create new images from modified containers.

Steps
Run a container interactively:

podman run -it --name myalpine docker.io/library/alpine:latest /bin/sh
Make changes inside container:

touch /testfile
echo "Lab 12" > /testfile
exit
Commit the container:

podman commit myalpine my_custom_alpine:v1
Verify new image:

podman images
podman run --rm my_custom_alpine:v1 cat /testfile
Should show "Lab 12" output

Use Case
This is useful when you need to:

Save a container's state for debugging
Create custom images without Dockerfiles
Preserve configurations made at runtime
Task 4: Understanding Limitations
Key Considerations
Tarball Portability:

Saved images are architecture-specific
An image saved on x86_64 won't work on ARM systems
Commit Limitations:

podman commit --help | grep -A5 "Limitations"
Doesn't capture:
Running processes
Volumes
Network configurations
Storage Requirements:

podman system df
Shows disk usage - commits and saves consume additional space

